title: For Sale:  House Bill 1231
postcontent: Indiana House Bill 1231 is looking to allow use of .243, 30-30, .308, 30-06, and .300 rifles from 2016 through 2020 deer firearms season.  The bill is still under revision, but the concept is to allow these 5 rifle cartridges for a 5 year period, which will be evaluated by state officials at the end of the 5 years.  It is all pretty poorly written at this point, not specifying .243 or .308 as being .243 or .308 Winchester (the assumed calibers that they mean) or clarifying what ".300" cartridge they are implying.  In addition, there is a provision to allow handguns with a "10mm bullet" for deer as well.  This is likely the 10mm auto, but it does not clearly spell that out either.  This is something to keep an eye on, much like last year's rifle debate.  Speak with your local officials and stay informed, or not.  After all, its my and your hunting seasons that are affected by these decisions. FYI, I have not voiced my opinion on this matter and I really don't care about yours either, so please don't bomb my email with hate responses.  Thanks.

Romarm Model GP WASR 10/63 Caliber 7.62x39 Firearm Type RifleBarrel 16in Fun Fact WASR-series rifles are manufactured with stamped sheet metal receivers that were originally intended for single-stack magazines. Featuring hard chrome-lined barrels, side-mount scope rail and wooden stocks, WASR-series rifles are commonly imported to the United States by Century International Arms. At the Century International Arms factory, the rifles are modified to conform with certain United States firearms regulations particular Title 18, Chapter 44, Section 922(r) of the United States Code, which deals with unlawful acts related to firearms. For example, the magazine wells are typically widened to accept standard AK double-stack column box magazines. Other common modifications include installation of upgraded gas pistons, fire control groups (i.e. trigger), pistol grips, and plastic folding or collapsible stocks manufactured by TAPCO of Georgia. Older WASR-series rifles commonly caused trigger slap, which is caused by the bolt slamming backward into the trigger assembly and causing significant pain to the shooter's trigger finger.[1] Beginning in 2007, Century International Arms has installed the TAPCO Intrafuse AK G2 trigger group, virtually eliminating the trigger slap problem. Rifles with this trigger group will have "TAPCO USA G2" stamped on the left side of the trigger. Some of these rifles may exhibit canted front sight blocks and gas tubes. WASR-series rifles are inexpensive and easily customized, with hundreds of aftermarket stocks, muzzle brakes, flash suppressors, telescopic sights, and other accessories available.

title: For Sale:  12g Mobil Choke Set (for Berretta, Benelli, CZ and Huglu)
location: Hartford, 60 miles S. of Topeka, Topeka, Kansas
postcontent: Got these Italian made FACTORY chokes with a Huglu Custom Shotgun a few months back.  Shot about 5-10 shots through each before getting new Carlson tubes to replace these.  They are stainless steel flush mount, no frills tubes that look just like the Carlson flush mount tubes you'll see going for about $20 each.  The set has FOUR chokes: Full (4/4), IM (3/4), M (2/4) and IC (1/4) and like all factory chokes shooting steel shot through the Full and Improved Modified chokes is a "no-no".  But you can use lead, Hevi-shot or copper plated through all chokes.  Steel through the Modified or IC is also ok (and give the same patterns as lead Full and IM respectively).The set comes with a choke wrench and fitted, black plastic box to hold the four chokes (and wrench) as well as a few Q-tips or patches in a nice small box-- fits easily in my shotgun case beside the barrel (where I wrap it in a oil cloth).  When done shooting, it's always a good idea to pull the chokes, lube them and the barrel (Q-tips work perfect) BEFORE leaving the feild.  Set is clean and look "as new".  All four chokes fit both my barrels (in my over/under) well, but the IM choke is a bit tight going down in my top barrel-- but still threads fine by hand and shot fine when I used it.  These have the standard end-notch ID system so you can easily see what choke is in the barrel without having to remove it.Bargain set and for those wanting matched chokes for a "mobil choke" shotgun, here's a way to have two tubes for each choke.  My new Carslons shoot no better than these did- but they look cooler and cost a LOT more.  So I probably should have just kept these and been happy.  But I don't need these now so here they are and I'll ship them for a flat $50 OR meet nearby Emporia, KS (or around SE Kansas on a weekend)

title: For Sale:  Mossberg 500CG
postcontent: Mossberg 500CG**LAYAWAY AVAILABLE** Condition Used great condition Price $225.00**Harvey Special** Inventory # G-1004572-1 Manufacturer Mossberg Model 500CG Caliber 20 Guage Firearm Type Shotgun Barrel 28in Fun Fact Introduced in 1961, all model 500s are based on the same basic concept designed by Carl Benson. Originally using a single action bar, that was known to bind and even break, this was changed to dual action bars in 1970, following the expiration of Remington's patent on the double action bar design. A single large locking lug is used to secure the breech. The magazine tube is located below the barrel, and is screwed into the receiver. The slide release is located to the left rear of the trigger guard, and the safety is located on the upper rear of the receiver (often called a "tang safety"). Sights vary from model to model, from simple bead sight to a receiver mounted ghost ring or an integrated base for a telescopic sight. Most models come with the receiver drilled and tapped for the installation of a rear sight or a scope base. The factory scope base is attached to the barrel via a cantilever-type mount, which places the scope over the receiver but keeps it with the barrel if the barrel is removed. Intended for use in harsh and dirty conditions, such as waterfowl hunting or combat, the Model 500 series is designed to be easy to clean and maintain. All Model 500s feature interchangeable barrels (given a particular gun's magazine capacity—a barrel designed for a five-shot tube will not fit a gun with a seven-shot tube), which may be removed without the use of tools, by loosening a screw on the end of the magazine tube, allowing the barrel to be removed. The bolt locks into a locking lug located on the top of the barrel, ensuring a solid bolt-to-barrel connection and not relying on the receiver for any locking strength. The trigger assembly, which includes the trigger, hammer, sear, and trigger body with guard, can be removed by pushing out one retaining pin and pulling downwards on the guard (if a pistol grip is installed, it usually must be removed first as virtually all such grips obstruct the removal of the trigger body). The elevator can be removed by putting the gun on safety and squeezing the sides together, freeing the pivot pins from the receiver. The forend can then be moved to the rear, allowing the bolt and bolt carrier to drop out, and then the forend can be removed by moving it forward. The cartridge stop and interrupter will then fall free, leaving just the ejector and the safety in the receiver, held in by screws. The magazine spring and follower may be removed by unscrewing the tube from the receiver (this may be difficult on some new 500s). This level of field stripping is sufficient to allow all components to be cleaned.
